,"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe inguinal ligament is an important anatomical structure in the lower abdomen. It extends from the anterior superior iliac spine to the pubic tubercle and plays a role in the formation of the inguinal canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the inguinal ligament is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eform the base of the inguinal canal\u003C/strong\u003E. This canal is a passageway in the lower abdominal wall that allows structures such as the spermatic cord in men and the round ligament in women to pass from the abdomen to the external genitalia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupports the abdominal organs\u003C/strong\u003E - The inguinal ligament does not directly support abdominal organs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnects the femur to the pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of ligaments like the iliofemoral ligament\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStabilises the hip joint\u003C/strong\u003E - The inguinal ligament does not stabilise the hip joint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates hip flexion\u003C/strong\u003E - The inguinal ligament does not play a role in hip movement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the role of the inguinal ligament is important in the context of inguinal hernias and other conditions affecting the lower abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The inguinal ligament forms the base of the inguinal canal, which is important for the passage of structures such as the spermatic cord in men and the round ligament in women.","The inguinal ligament is a key anatomical landmark that separates the abdomen from the thigh.","The inguinal ligament is formed by the lower border of the external oblique aponeurosis."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18249"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T08:09:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T08:10:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10963"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73947"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical 